  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When you sell an investment property, the rent it currently earns is not just a number on a tenancy schedule. For investors in the buyer pool, it is a direct input into whether they will bid and how much they will pay. For owner-occupiers looking at the same property, yield is irrelevant. Understanding which type of buyer dominates your suburb and price bracket, and how your current tenancy terms interact with that buyer pool, is one of the more consequential decisions you will make before you list.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What rental yield is and how buyers use it</h2>
      <p>Gross rental yield is annual rent divided by purchase price, expressed as a percentage. A property renting for $600 per week ($31,200 per year) purchased for $900,000 has a gross yield of 3.47%. Net yield strips out holding costs: council rates, body corporate fees, landlord insurance, property management fees, and maintenance. For a typical Queensland investment property, the gap between gross and net yield is commonly 1 to 1.5 percentage points. The same property might show 3.47% gross but only 2.1% net after costs.</p>

      <p>Investor buyers use gross yield as a quick screening tool when browsing listings. Net yield is what they actually model when they sit down to assess whether a property makes financial sense at a given price. Sophisticated buyers will ask for a full income and expense statement; less experienced investors may rely on the gross figure alone. Either way, your rent is doing work on their spreadsheet whether you think of it that way or not.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How below-market rent reduces what investors will pay</h2>
      <p>If your property is tenanted at below-market rent, investor buyers will discount their offer accordingly. A home renting for $480 per week when comparable properties are achieving $600 represents a $6,240 annual shortfall in income. An investor looking at a 3.5% gross yield target would, in theory, be willing to pay approximately $178,000 less for that property than they would for an identical one at market rent. The mathematics of yield compression is that direct.</p>

      <p>Below-market rent situations are common. Long-term tenants who have not had rent reviews, lease renewals negotiated at locked-in rates, or landlords who have prioritised occupancy stability over rent growth can all produce this outcome. Sellers sometimes discover the gap only when they ask their agent to prepare a marketing appraisal and the agent points out what the property could be achieving. At that point, you have three options: re-let at market before selling, sell with the existing tenancy and accept the investor discount, or wait for the lease to expire and sell vacant.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Above-market rent and what it does to buyer interest</h2>
      <p>The converse is also true. A property renting at above-market rates, or on a fixed-term lease with annual increases locked in, can attract a premium from yield-focused investors. If comparable properties are renting for $550 and yours is on a lease achieving $640, that differential is real income to a buyer. In strong rental markets like Brisbane's inner east has experienced over recent years, well-structured leases with good tenants and above-market rents can genuinely widen investor buyer interest and support a stronger price.</p>

      <p>In practice, however, the uplift from above-market rent is usually smaller than the discount from below-market rent. Buyers are typically more cautious about overpaying than they are motivated by a modest income premium. The asymmetry is worth understanding: a strong tenancy helps, but a weak tenancy hurts more.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why owner-occupiers often pay more than investors in the inner east</h2>
      <p>Brisbane's inner-east suburbs, Camp Hill, Morningside, Bulimba, Norman Park, Hawthorne, have consistently attracted strong owner-occupier demand. Families buying for school catchments, lifestyle proximity, and emotional connection to a home routinely outbid investors on the same property. An owner-occupier buying a well-presented Queenslander does not care what it rents for. They are not modelling yield. They are deciding how much they want to live there.</p>

      <p>This has a direct implication for how you approach a sale. If your property has broad owner-occupier appeal, selling it vacant or with a short lease expiry coming up will typically produce a better result than selling it tenanted at below-market rent, because you open up the larger, less price-sensitive buyer pool. The investor who is constrained by yield thresholds is outcompeted by the owner-occupier who has no yield floor at all.</p>

      <p>If your property is a genuine investment-grade asset, newer construction, strong yield, good body corporate, in a pocket that does not attract as many owner-occupiers, then marketing directly to investors with transparent financial information is the right approach. In that case, above-market rent and a well-maintained tenancy become genuine marketing assets.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When to wait for the lease to expire before selling</h2>
      <p>If your property is currently tenanted at below-market rent and has owner-occupier appeal, the question of whether to wait for the lease to expire is worth serious analysis. It comes down to comparing the likely price uplift from selling vacant against the holding costs and opportunity cost of waiting. For a property where the owner-occupier premium is material and the tenancy is significantly below market, the waiting calculation often favours patience.</p>

      <p>In Queensland, you generally cannot end a periodic tenancy without notice requirements being met, and ending a fixed-term lease requires the tenant's agreement or a specific ground. If your property is on a fixed-term lease with significant time remaining, your options are more constrained. Understanding the tenancy terms clearly before you decide to sell is essential, and your agent should be able to walk you through the implications of each scenario before you commit to a launch timeline.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to present rental history honestly in marketing</h2>
      <p>Whatever your tenancy situation, presenting the rental history and income potential honestly is both a legal obligation and a practical necessity. Buyers and their agents will verify the figures. Tenancy schedules, rental receipts, and property management statements are all discoverable at or before due diligence. Overstating income potential or obscuring below-market rent creates problems at the point where buyers engage solicitors, and experienced investor buyers will identify the issue and may walk away or renegotiate after contract.</p>

      <p>The more useful approach is to present the current rent, the market rent estimate, and the tenancy terms clearly, and let buyers make their own assessment. If you are below market, framing it as an opportunity for a buyer to bring rents to market at lease renewal is not misleading; it is accurate, and some investors specifically seek out this type of property. What you must not do is imply that a below-market rent is current market rent.</p>

